The empty column is the contribution. Decomposition is everywhere, for scale, for memory, or for unbounded computation. Recombination is well studied, through folding, aggregation, and proof-carrying data. But no line treats the privacy of the decomposition structure as a first-class, measured dimension on a concrete combinatorial statement. The nearest exception is the commit-and-prove row, where a commitment's hiding does protect the values inside each piece; but that hides the piece's _contents_, not the partition---where the cut was made---and it is offered as a building block, not measured as a privacy axis. The column stays empty in the sense that matters. That, together with the dualism and the stitching-tax framing that organize every row above into one frontier, is what this thesis adds.

A second, smaller difference is in how the comparison is run. General benchmarking efforts for zero-knowledge systems measure libraries, circuits, and whole proving stacks for throughput @ernstberger2024zkbench; the systems above are compared the same way. This thesis measures under a discipline built instead for the question it asks. Comparisons are made only within a fixed privacy level, never across one. Each comparison changes exactly one thing, and the change that would alter two at once is named and forbidden---the forbidden diagonal. And both totals are reported: the total work, which decomposition conserves, and the parallel wall-clock, which is where the win actually appears. That discipline also forces an honest look at the metrics themselves, including one count that tracks the proving cost far less well than it appears to, which we examine in @chap:results.

With the map drawn and the gap named, the rest of the thesis fills it. @chap:methodology builds the monolithic baseline the decomposed constructions answer to. @chap:hierarchical develops the framework---the dualism, the stitching tax, the frontier---and walks down the privacy ladder one construction at a time. @chap:results measures them, and @chap:conclusions returns to the frontier to ask which corner is worth building next.
